With #394 applied, any trampoline class that tries to override a function returning a reference or pointer to a primitive type (essentially any of the type_casters that copy a value, such as numeric, std::string, std::complex if `complex.h` is included, etc., and anything else using PYBIND11_TYPE_CASTER) are going to fail.  Between ed14879a1942fdfa4e4ef053c842841ca9fd6fc4 (PR #297) and #394, it wouldn't compile at all; as of #394, it will work for non-converted types, and gives a static_assert compilation failure for primitive types.

Before ed14879a (including in v1.8.1) it compiled, but it was returning a reference to a temporary, as the following demonstrates:
```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
PYBIND11_PLUGIN(t) {
    namespace py = pybind11;
    py::module m("t");
    m.def("foo", [](py::object o) { std::cout << o.cast<std::string &>() << "\n"; });
    return m.ptr();
}
```

```Python
import t
t.foo("asdf" * 10)
```
`python test.py | xxd` shows the obvious problem:
```
00000000: 884b e87d 897f 0000 c07b 7a02 0000 0000  .K.}.....{z.....
00000010: 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466  asdfasdfasdfasdf
00000020: 6173 6466 6173 6466 0a                   asdfasdf.
```
(the same code, but cast to a non-reference `std::string`, works as intended, of course):
```
00000000: 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466  asdfasdfasdfasdf
00000010: 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466 6173 6466  asdfasdfasdfasdf
00000020: 6173 6466 6173 6466 0a                   asdfasdf.
```

The fact that an explicit `obj.cast<int &>()` doesn't compile now is not a big deal, but a bigger implication of this is that we cannot override a method that returns a reference (including a `const Type &`).  This isn't something new: we never *could* do such an override properly, but it did actually compile before and gave the appearance of working--it just returned a reference to already-freed memory.

I think, at the very least, it needs to be documented that this isn't supported, but it would be nicer still if we had a suggested workaround.  I thought something like this might work:

```C++
    class A {
        std::string v = "jkl;";
    public:
        virtual const std::string &value() { return v; }
        void print() { py::print(value()); }
    };
    class PyA : public A {
        std::string _value;
        std::string _value_helper() { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(std::string, A, value); }
        std::string &value() override { _value = _value_helper(); return _value; }
    };

    py::module m("t");
    py::class_<A, PyA>(m, "A")
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("value", &A::value)
        .def("print", &A::print);
```

... but it doesn't; I get a segfault instead where the assignment to _value happens (because, apparently, the trampoline instance is never actually initialized--which is fine as long as it doesn't have any members).  So:

1. Should we document it as not supported?
2. Should we make the above work, by actually initializing the trampoline instance?
3. Should we find and document some other workaround?
